Not sure I understand. Is your comment in reference to line 1511 (old file), where I replaced

char * saveLobDataFile = new(getLobGlobalHeap()) char[MAX_LOB_FILE_NAME_LEN+6];

with

string saveLobDataFile = lobDataFile_ + "_save";

The reason I did that was that lobDataFile_ is a string, and it made the code cleaner if I used the same model for saveLobDataFile and lobDataFile_. Note that the string is a stack variable, so its destructor is called when it goes out of scope.

I could have coded

NAString saveLobDataFile(getLobGlobalHeap());
saveLobDataFile = lobDataFile_.c_str();
saveLobDataFile += "_save";

but that seems a bit ugly.

Later when lobDataFile_ is changed to an NAString, we could code this more cleanly as

NAString saveLobDataFile(getLobGlobalHeap()) = lobDataFile_ + "_save";

Wouldn't it be better to do this when lobDataFile_ is changed to an NAString?
